surveys.narrative: The walleye gillnet catch rate in 1998 was 7.60 fish per net, the third highest index of abundance for Rainy Lake on record. The historical average was 5.20. Several strong year-classes were present in the catch. The 1995 year-class dominated contributing 30% to the total. In 1999, these fish should average 13-15 inches in length and provide the bulk of the angler harvest. The 1994 year-class also contributed substantially to the 1998 catch. In 1999 these fish will average 15-17 inches in length with many of the faster growing individuals entering the protected size range beginning at 17 inches (the Minnesota waters of Rainy Lake have an experimental regulation in place requiring the release of walleye between 17 and 25 inches in length. One walleye over 25 inches may be kept in a possession limit of 6 fish). The 1996 year-class also contributed substantially to the 1998 catch. These fish averaged 10 inches during the fall of 1998 but should grow to an acceptable size for harvest in 1999. Other strong year-classes present in the fishery include 1991 and 1997. The 1998 gillnet catch of walleye over 17 inches was at its lowest level since 1994. Prior to 1998, the abundance of walleye over 17 inches had been steadily increasing over several years. The decline may be related to poor year-classes that hatched during the springs of 1992 and 1993. These year-classes should be contributing the bulk of the catch of fish over 17 inches in length. Instead, the strong 1991 year-class contributed most of the fish caught over 17 inches. Abundance of large fish should rebound in 1999 as individuals of the 1994 year-class grow into the protected length interval. The gillnet catch rate of northern pike was 2.00, slightly higher than that recorded in 1997 but still below the historicalaverage of 2.79. The pike catch was dominated by young fish. Age-2 and 3 fish contributed 58% of the 1998 catch. As a result, the number of fish over 21 inches in length was at a 20 year low. The sauger gillnet catch rate was 2.10, the second lowest index of abundance on record. The 1998 catch fell within thebottom 25% of all catches from large softwater lakes similar to Rainy. There is little evidence that sauger abundance will improve in the near future. Sauger make up a minor component of the angler harvest on Rainy Lake. The black crappie trapnet catch improved for the second straight year increasing to 2.11. The index of abundance,however, was still well below levels recorded in the early 1990's. Crappie size structure has shifted to younger and smaller fish,however, 1.0-1.5 pound fish are still caught on occasion. Results of the 1998 open water creel survey for Rainy Lake indicate that fishing effort continues to increase as word of theimproved fishery spreads. The estimate of effort exceeded 240,000 angler-hours and was 30% greater than the previous high recorded in 1997.

The 2006 large lake sampling program provided valuable insight to the status of the Rainy Lake fishery. Walleye, yellow perch, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and black crappie populations are doing well as indicated by various sampling methods. Several trends in the long-term gill net data show the Rainy Lake walleye fishery has recovered from years of overharvest and continual suppression seen through the early 1990s.

The 2006 gill netted walleye catch consisted of 15 age groups. Ages ranged from age-0 to age-17 with a mean of 4.6 years. Age-3 walleye made up 35.0% of the gill-net catch while age-5 accounted for 22.7%. Lengths of gill netted walleye ranged from 4.3 to 26.8 inches. The mean walleye length was 13.6 inches and the mean weight was 1.10 pounds.

For the past 12 years walleye gill net CPUE has been at historically high levels. The 2006 CPUE was the third highest since the large lake program began in 1983. Rainy Lake walleye abundance has reached a new peak. Walleye CPUE from 1983 to 1994 averaged 3.98 per net, since 1995 the average is 7.14 per net. Only twice (2001 and 2002) during the past ten years has the walleye CPUE been below six per net. Consistent recruitment has been the main factor contributing to the observed increase in CPUE.

Catch rates of larger walleye (over 17") have significantly increased in the past 30 years. During the past 12 years the CPUE of walleye over 17 inches has remained greater than one per net, a feat that was achieved only twice prior to 1990. Currently walleye greater than 17 inches (and less than 28 inches) are protected by length regulations.

Recruitment, expressed as year-class strength, is more consistent and higher than it was 15 years ago. Prior to the 1990s Rainy Lake walleye produced a strong year-class once every four years. Throughout the 1990s, six out of the 10 year-classes were rated as strong. Netting surveys show that the 2000 year-class is weak. However, the 2001 year-class stands to be the strongest on record. Indications of the 2002 and 2004 year-classes are weak. In contrast the 2003, 2005, and 2006 are very strong.

Throughout the history of monitoring and management on Rainy Lake we have observed the recovery of the walleye population. Indications from recent sampling are that the population has reached a plateau and has remained sustainable at the current population structure. Current regulations have directed harvest on Minnesota waters to sustainable yields.

Walleye fishing should remain exceptional on Rainy Lake. There are several strong year-classes within the protected slot that should provide good catch rates of large walleye and uphold reproduction. The 2001 and 2003 year-classes will continue to be main contributors to the harvest. While the 2005 and 2006 year-classes are showing good potential, it will be a couple of years before they begin recruitment to the sport fishery.

Northern pike gill-net CPUE has been low for the past three years. Northern pike assessment shows there are several average year-classes present in the catch; however, recruitment may be slowing. While large northern pike were present there was a downward trend in pike growth rates during the late 1990s into the early 2000s, this trend has changed and growth rates are increasing while recruitment is slowing. During the early 1990s mean northern pike length at age-3 was approximately 23 inches, during the late 1990s into the early 2000s length at age-3 dropped into the mid to upper teen range. In 2006 the mean northern pike length for age-3 was 20.4 inches, illustrating the faster growth rates.

Spring sampling indicated the black crappie population is in a transitional phase. Younger year-classes were present and mortality (natural and fishing) has greatly reduced the population of the strong year-classes from the mid-1990s. Recruitment is necessary to bring the crappie numbers back to trap net numbers observed in the early 2000s. The variable recruitment of crappie in Rainy Lake is consistent with crappie populations from around the country.

Smallmouth bass numbers from the nighttime electrofishing indicates good recruitment. The 2006 smallmouth bass CPUE was near normal for Rainy Lake. Smallmouth bass populations have grown and have been protected only by the catch-and-release ethics common to most bass anglers. Bass growth on Rainy Lake is slow compared to area and state averages. However, there are plenty of memorable and trophy sized smallmouth bass present as demonstrated by the catch during the spring electrofishing and reports from anglers. Angler opportunities in 2007 should remain good.

The 2009 field season on Rainy Lake was in many ways similar to 2008. A cold spring appears to have delayed growth for the lakes coolwater species even more so than in 2008. Below normal temperatures and windy conditions kept surface water temperatures low until late August before they peaked in early to mid September. When combined with the high water experienced in the spring these cold temperatures may have contributed to a second year of higher than normal catches of coregonids in several of our gears including record catches of lake whitefish in the annual fall gill-net assessment.

High numbers of walleye were again encountered in seine hauls at predictably small sizes given the cool water temperatures. We again experienced an abnormally warm fall with peak water temperatures occurring during our fall gill-net assessment. Our catch rate for walleyes rebounded to slightly above the average catch rate for Rainy Lake. Much of this rebound was driven by strong recruitment from the 2006 year class that is growing into the holes left by a nearly absent 2004 year class. No creel was conducted in 2009 due to fiscal limitations, but anecdotal reports indicated that, much like 2008, 2009 was characterized by good catches of large fish protected by the 17"-28" protected slot and fish smaller than the harvest size for most anglers.

Despite confounding environmental factors the 2009 large lake sampling program provided valuable insight to the status of the Rainy Lake fishery. Walleye, yellow perch, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and black crappie populations are healthy as indicated by various sampling methods.

For the past 14 years walleye gill net CPUE has been at historically high levels. The 2009 CPUE of 5.79 per gill net was up slightly from the 4.83 per gill net captured in 2008. Walleye CPUE from 1983 to 1994 averaged 3.98 per net, since 1995 the average is 7.77 per net. Consistent recruitment has been the main factor contributing to the observed increase in CPUE.

Several factors may have contributed to the reduced numbers of walleye in the gill nets during recent years. A warm fall with water temperatures above normal for the time of year may have negatively affected the success of our fall netting. The below average temperatures during the summers of 2008 and 2009 certainly led to slower growth rates which may be affecting gill-net catchability of younger walleyes. The mean length of age-1 through age-4 fish in 2009 was from 1.0" to 1.9" lower than the mean length at capture for their respective ages from 1998-2008. The age-5 and age-6 fish also experienced the cold summer of 2004 and show even slower growth being 4.1" and 2.4" below the 1998-2008 mean length. Additionally, poor production during 2002 and a near total failure of the 2004 year-class translates to poor numbers of 13-17 inch walleye in the gill net catch. Only age-2, -3, -6, and -8 walleye were caught rates above normal for their respective ages.

Catch rates of larger walleye (over 17") have significantly increased in the past 30 years. After the CPUE of walleye over 17 inches in 2008 dipped below one per net for the first time since the protected slot was put in place it rebounded slightly to 1.33 per net in 2009. Currently walleye greater than 17 inches (and less than 28 inches) are protected by length regulations. Creel data from 2008 indicated that walleye 17 inches or greater in length made up 39% of the total catch for 2008 which had the highest walleye catch on record for Rainy Lake.

Recruitment, expressed as year-class strength, is more consistent and higher than it was 15 years ago. Prior to the 1990s Rainy Lake walleye produced a strong year-class once every four years. Throughout the 1990s, six out of the ten year-classes were rated as strong. During the first half of the 2000s three of the seven year-classes recruited to date are strong including record breaking 2001 year class and the 2006 year-class which recruited to the gear in 2009. Early indications are that one or two more strong year-classes are likely awaiting recruitment, though slower growth due to recent cool summers may expose them to predation longer and delay full recruitment to the gill nets.

Seining and electrofishing data have been used to predict future walleye year-class strength on Rainy Lake. Prior to 1995 length data from summer seining provided the most reliable predictors. Since 1995 electrofishing indices have been more significant. This change may have arrived from changes in growth observed during the past 15 years. Seining data indicated the 2009 year-class will be weak, while the electrofishing data indicates it will be average. The unique weather associated with the initial growth of the 2009 year-class may make it difficult to predict which model will be more accurate. A cold spring and summer appears to have slowed summer growth for juvenile fish, but with some of the warmest surface temperatures of the year encountered over an extended period in September the length of the growing season may have been extended.

Walleye fishing should remain exceptional on Rainy Lake. There are several strong year-classes within the protected slot that should provide good catch rates of large walleye and uphold reproduction. The 2003 and 2006 year-classes will continue to be the main contributor to the harvest, though the most recent creel indicated that contributions from the poor 2005 year-class were already recruiting to the sport fishery in 2008. The 2007 year-class is showing good potential, and will likely begin to contribute heavily to the sport fishery over the next several years.

Northern pike gillnet CPUE decreased to below the first quartile for Rainy Lake in 2009 after a sharp increase in 2007 and equally sharp decline in 2008. Northern pike densities have great influence on northern pike growth; northern pike growth is negatively correlated with pike abundance (Pierce and Tomcko 2003, Pierce et al. 2003). Northern pike assessment shows there are several average year-classes present in the catch. The 2005 year-class has emerged as being strong. While large northern pike were present there was a downward trend in pike growth rates during the late 1990s into the early 2000s, this trend has changed and growth rates are increasing while recruitment is slowing. During the early 1990s mean northern pike length at age-3 was approximately 23 inches, during the late 1990s into the early 2000s length at age-3 dropped into the mid to upper teen range. In 2009 the mean northern pike length for age-3 was 22.11 inches, illustrating the faster growth rates.

Sauger abundance has steadily declined for the past 16 years. The CPUE observed in 2009 was tied for the lowest ever with 2008. This trend may demonstrate density dependent and interspecies competition that influences the abundance and growth of walleye and sauger. Staggs and Ottis (1996) found that competition did exist between walleye and sauger and that regardless both species grew better in years with high forage abundance. Sauger fishing on Rainy Lake is a result of indirect catch, no angling parties contacted during 2008 were targeting sauger (Schlesser 2009). Low sauger abundance, small average size, and a healthy walleye fishery likely are the cause for effort being directed towards walleye.

Lake whitefish are commercially fished on Rainy Lake and there is very little sport-fishing effort directed toward this species. Annual commercial harvest of lake whitefish has remained below the target quota every year since 1999. FCIN provides a standardized methodology for monitoring of this population. Based on four years of observation the lake whitefish population is showing no signs of overexploitation, however, more years of observation are needed to quantify this statement. Good recruitment in the past five years indicates the population is sustainable. FCIN is scheduled to be conducted again during the summers of 2011-12.

Spring sampling indicated the black crappie population is doing very well. Younger year-classes were present and mortality (natural and fishing) has greatly reduced the population of the strong year-classes from the mid-1990s. The recruitment of the 2003 year-class to the sport fishery (and trap nets) has resulted in a very abundant fishery with exceptional opportunities to catch crappies. The 2008 creel reported the highest harvest of crappies ever recorded for Rainy Lake. The variable recruitment of crappie in Rainy Lake is consistent with crappie populations from around the country (Sammons et al 2002 and Allen 1997). The current status of the fishery indicates that crappie fishing should be exceptional during the next few years as the 2003 year-class contributes numbers of fish and the 2005 year class grows more fully into the acceptable size for harvest.

The 2009 smallmouth bass CPUE was down considerably from normal for Rainy Lake, but again was likely affected by the cold spring temperatures. Smallmouth bass populations have grown and have been protected only by the catch-and-release ethics common to most bass anglers. Bass growth on Rainy Lake is slow compared to area and state averages. However, there are plenty of memorable and trophy sized smallmouth bass present as demonstrated by the catch during the spring electrofishing and reports from anglers. Angler opportunities in 2010 should remain good.

Yellow perch gill-net numbers were above the third quartile for Rainy Lake. The length distribution of perch captured in the gill nets was predominantly in the less than nine-inch category. However, 25% of the perch sampled were more than nine inches in length and they should provide some decent harvest opportunities for the next few years. With the exception of 2004 recruitment has been exceptional for the past eight years, providing a strong forage base and developing angling opportunities.

Rainy Lake is part of the statewide Large Lake Program, an intensive fisheries management program on the 10 largest lakes in Minnesota. The Large Lake Program includes annual population assessments, annual water quality monitoring, and regularly scheduled creel surveys. A variety of sampling gear is used during population assessments to collect the various fish species and life stages. These gear types include gill nets, beach seines, and an electrofishing boat on Rainy Lake. Sampling for each gear type is conducted at the same time and place each year in order to determine population trends for the major species. Data is also collected on length, weight, age, and growth for each of the major species.

The walleye gillnet catch in 2016 was 5.2 fish/net, which is near the historic median for Rainy Lake. For the past 18 years the Walleye gill net catch rate has been at historically high levels. The Walleye catch rate from 1983 to 1994 averaged 3.98 per net; since 1995 the average is 7.42 per net. The 2015 and 2016 catch rates were down from the 7.96 per gill net captured in 2013 but within the range from recent years. Age 4 walleyes from the 2012 year-class composed the largest portion of the catch at 21.0 percent. The 2011 year-class is the most recent strong year-class to recruit to the fishery. However, this large year-class is growing slower than average for Rainy ranging from 10.7 to 17.7 inches long and averaging 13.6 inches in the 2016 survey. Overall, gillnetted Walleyes ranged in length from 5.2 to 25.7 inches long and had an average length of 13.3 inches. There is a special regulation for Walleye on Rainy Lake; an 18-26 inch protected slot, with one fish allowed over 26 inches, and a four-fish bag limit. The goal of the regulation is to keep harvest at a safe level and maintain adequate spawning stock.

Sauger numbers are low, growth is slow, and they generally do not reach a large size in Rainy Lake. Occasionally larger Sauger are encountered in the Black Bay area. The overall gill net catch rate was 1.63 Sauger/net in 2016. Lengths ranged from 7.4 to 14.7 inches and averaged 10.3 inches.

The gillnet catch of Northern Pike was 1.75 fish/net, lower than the historic average for Rainy. Northern Pike catch rates have been consistently low in recent years. However, Northern Pike grow relatively fast and reach large and even trophy sizes. Pike ranged from 17.2 to 36.9 inches in 2016. The average length was 23.5 inches. Reports of anglers catching large Northern Pike 40 inches or longer are not uncommon on Rainy Lake.

Yellow Perch numbers and sizes have increased in recent years in Rainy Lake. The 2016 gill net catch rate was lower than recent surveys at 5.83 fish/net and slightly lower than the historic average. Yellow Perch lengths ranged from 4.8 to 11.7 inches and the overall average was 8.3 inches. Yellow perch size structure has improved over time providing more opportunity for anglers to harvest quality-sized fish. Fifty-five percent of the 2016 gill net catch measured eight inches or longer and 21 percent were 10 inches or longer.

An electrofishing boat is used as the standard sampling gear for smallmouth bass because they are not effectively caught in standard assessment nets. Thirty-four smallmouth bass were caught while electrofishing in 2016 for a catch rate of 21.1 fish/hour, similar to what has been seen in recent surveys. Lengths ranged from 3.9 to 19.3 inches and averaged 11.5 inches. Smallmouth Bass growth on Rainy Lake is slow compared to area and state averages. However, there are memorable and trophy sized smallmouth bass present. Smallmouth bass over 19 inches are often caught in our sampling gear including a 19.3 inch bass caught during electrofishing in 2016. A smallmouth bass measuring 19.2 inches long and weighing 4.4 pounds was caught in a 2013 gill net on Rainy Lake. Smallmouth bass harvest numbers are very low on Rainy Lake, and angler opportunities in 2016 should remain good.

Trap nets are set in Black Bay and the lower Rat Root River each spring targeting Black Crappies. A total of 115 crappies were caught in 2016 for a catch rate of 5.75 per net. This catch rate is lower than 2015 but among the highest ever recorded for Rainy Lake. Lengths ranged from 5.4 to 15.0 inches and averaged 11.0 inches. Fifty-one percent of the catch was from the 2012 year-class. Three consecutive years of good Black Crappie production and recruitment on Rainy from 2010-2012 is driving the increase in numbers. The 2010 year-class averaged 12.3 inches long while the 2012 year-class averaged 10.1 inches in 2016. Eighty percent of the Black Crappies caught in the 2016 survey were over 10 inches long and 30 percent were 12 inches or longer. The high catch rates and large sizes will provide good angler opportunities over the next few years.

Rainy Lake is known to be infested with spiny waterfleas. Anglers and boaters should always take preventative measures to avoid moving invasive species to other lakes. For more information on invasive species and other DNR programs, go to the DNR website at mndnr.gov.

Walleye gillnet CPUE increased in 2002 to 5.6 per net (Table 1, Figure 1). The 2002 gillnetting CPUE was above the long-term mean, falling between the median and third quartile. Sand Bay produced a walleye CPUE of 9.5, this is nearly a 50% increase from last years catch but is the second lowest level since being added as a station in 1998. The four year mean of the Sand Bay sets is 15.5 per net. Surface water temperatures during the sampling were higher than normal for this time of year and may have effected gillnetting success.Initial aging of walleye indicated that 12 year-classes were present in the gillnet catch. The 1998 (age-4) and 2001(age-1) year-classes each contributed over 20% to the walleye gillnet catch. The CPUE for age-4 walleye of 1.25, was well above the 20 year mean of 0.90 per net. The mean length of the age-4 walleye was 12.3 inches, ranging from 8.6 to 15.4 inches. The 1998 year-class should make a strong contribution to the angler catch and harvest throughout the 2003 season. The CPUE for age-1 walleye was 1.15, doubling the 20 year mean of 0.57 per net. The mean length of age-1 walleye was 7.1 inches. The 2001 year-class will likely be a small contributor to the harvest during the 2003 season, but should be a strong contributor in the future.In 2002 the catch rate of age-5 or greater walleye was 2.4 per net, this is a record high and well above the long-term mean of 1.43. Most notable were the 1997 (age-5) and 1995 (age-7) year-classes. The 1997 year-class as age-5 fish were caught at a CPUE of 0.75. The 1995 year-class as age-7 fish exhibited a higher CPUE (0.75) than the 1991 year-class as age-7's. None of the age-5 walleye collected were greater than 17 inches (mean = 14.5 inches), thus they should provide good harvest opportunities to anglers during 2003. Conversely, most of the 1995 year-class walleye collected were within the protected slot (length: mean = 18.0, min = 13.5, max = 20.0).Few individuals of the 2000 (age-2) walleye year-class were captured in the 2002 gillnet catch. The CPUE for age-2 walleye was 0.20 compared to a historical mean of 1.04. Results from previous surveys have suggested that the 2000 year-class was weak, our 2002 fall gillnetting assessment supports those results. The 1999 year-class was also collected in below average numbers. The CPUE of the 1999 (age-3) year-class was 0.55, which is less than half of the long-term mean of 1.12 age-3 fish per net.The northern pike gillnet CPUE was 2.6 per net, which is right at the historical median CPUE for Rainy Lake. Lengths ranged from 16.1 to 32.1 inches (Table 2) with a mean of 21.1 inches.The sauger gillnet CPUE of 1.85 was the lowest since 1985. The historical median was 3.60. The sauger length-frequency distribution was bimodal with peaks occurring at 8.5 inches and 12.0 inches. The lower peak was probably dominated by an apparent strong 1998 year-class. Previous assessments have indicated that no other strong year-classes are currently present in the fishery. The black crappie trap net CPUE reached a record high of 7.15 per net. From 1996 to 2000, CPUE had steadily increased from 0.94 per net to 5.11. In 2001 CPUE declined to a record low. Black crappie caught in the trap nets during our 2002 spring trap netting ranged from 2.7 to 14.3 inches with a mean of 10.8 inches. Anglers harvested an estimated 2,074 pounds of crappie from Rainy Lake in 2002, the second highest harvest since 1994. No parties interviewed by our clerk reached the inland daily and possession limit of 15. Targeting anglers produced a catch rate of 0.606 fish per angler hour and a harvest rate of 0.481. Harvested crappie had a mean length of 10.8 inches. Results of the 2002 summer angler creel survey indicated that angling effort decreased for the second year in a row. The estimated angler effort of 225,662 hours was the lowest level in the past five years, however still well above the long term mean of 168,192.Anglers caught an estimated 122,153 walleye, the second most on record. The 2002 walleye harvest rate of 0.169 was slightly below the historical mean of 0.175 fish per angler hour. The lower effort coupled with the lower harvest rate resulted in a total harvest of 38,158 walleye. Despite the low harvest rate, the total harvest was the fifth highest on record (since 1977). The total walleye yield was 35,988 pounds. An estimated 83,995 walleyes (172,445 pounds) walleye were caught and released during the 2002 open-water season. Of those walleyes released an estimated 6,292 (10,800 pounds) walleye were lost to hooking mortality. The mean targeting catch and harvest rates were 0.596 and 0.190, respectively. The mean targeting catch rate of walleye over 17 inches was 0.221.

The 2023 Walleye gill net catch rate was 7.5 fish/net, which is greater than the historic average of 6.1 fish/net for Rainy Lake. Walleye catch rates have increased following historic overfishing prior to the 1990s. Walleye numbers quickly increased as the population recovered in the 1990s and reached an all-time high of 10.0 Walleyes per net in 2004. The Walleye catch rate from 1983 to 1994 averaged 4.0 per net; since 1995 the average is 7.0 per net. Catch rates over the past 15 years have ranged from 4.6 to 8.0 Walleyes per gill net. Age-2 Walleyes from the 2021 year-class composed the largest portion of the 2023 catch at 24.4 percent. Most age-2 Walleyes in the 2023 survey were in the nine, ten, and eleven-inch length groups but overall ranged from 6.9 to 12.2 inches long. The 2023 survey also caught a good number of age-4 Walleyes from the 2019 year-class. Most fish from this year-class were in the 12- to 14-inch length groups but ranged in length from 9.4 to 18.5 inches long. Overall, the 2023 survey caught above average numbers of eight-to-14-inch Walleyes and below average numbers of 15-17-inch Walleyes. This high abundance of smaller fish in the system is the result of the above average 2019 and 2021 year-classes. There are fewer 15-17 inch Walleyes because of weak year-classes produced in 2017 and 2018. Anglers are likely to encounter more harvestable-sized fish over the next couple of years as the strong 2019 and 2021 year-classes continue to grow. Overall, gill netted Walleyes ranged in length from 3.7 to 27.4 inches and had an average length of 13.7 inches. There is a special regulation for Walleye on Rainy Lake; an 18-26 inch protected slot, with one fish allowed over 26 inches, and a four-fish bag limit. The goal of the regulation is to keep harvest at a safe level and maintain adequate spawning stock.

Reports of anglers catching large Northern Pike of 40 inches or longer are not uncommon on Rainy Lake.

Yellow Perch numbers and sizes were at historic highs from 2003-2012. The record high catch rate occurred in 2012 at 13.5/net. The 2023 gill net catch rate was 9.0/net which is greater than the long-term average for Rainy Lake. Rainy Lake saw good Perch production from the 2018, 2019, and 2020 year-classes. In fact, the 2020 year-class appears to be one of the strongest ever produced. Individuals from the 2020 year-class ranged in length from 6.1 to 9.4 inches but most were in the seven- and eight-inch length groups in 2023. Overall, 2023 Yellow Perch lengths ranged from 5.5 to 12.2 inches and the overall average was 8.3 inches. Yellow Perch size structure has improved over time providing more opportunity for anglers to harvest quality-sized fish.

Trap nets are set in Black Bay and the lower Rat Root River each spring targeting adult Black Crappies. A total of 170 crappies were caught in 2023 for a catch rate of 9.1 per net, which is among the highest ever on Rainy Lake. Black Crappie catch rates have been above average in six of the past seven surveys. Good Black Crappie production and recruitment on Rainy was observed from the 2016, 2017, 2019, and 2020 year-classes and is the driver of the high catch rates in recent years. Lengths ranged from 6.9 to 14.0 inches and averaged 10.7 inches in 2023. Twenty percent of the catch was from the 2019 year-class and an additional 19.4 percent from the 2016 year-class. Sixty-five percent of the Black Crappies caught in the 2023 survey were over 10 inches long and 29 percent were 12 inches or longer.

The 1999 fall investigation found walleye numbers remaining good at 7.0 per net compared to the long term average of 4.7. Strong year classes from 1991, 1994, 1996, and 1997 were present. The number of walleye over 17 inches, fish protected by the experimental regulation, increased to 1.5 per net compared to the long term average of 1.1 per net. The average walleye measured 13.5 inches. The slow growth rate was typical of large, natural walleye lakes in the International Falls area. Northern pike numbers were near the long term average of 2.8 pike per net, however, most of the northerns sampled in 1999 were young fish. Average length was 21.4 inches with a range from 16.5 to 27.4 inches. The black crappie trapnet catch improved for the third straight year, increasing to 2.4 per net. The average since 1992 was 2.6 per trapnet. Most of the sampled crappies were between 9 and 11 inches (average of 10.1 inches) and weighed an average of 3/4 of a pound. Sauger numbers, a minor component of the angler's catch, were low at 2.4 per net. Long term average was 4.5 per net. Average length was 10.6 inches with only 1 fish over 15 inches sampled in 1999. Fall electrofishing sampled smallmouth bass, especially young of the year, at a rate of 38.4 fish per hour. The historic average was 27.9 fish per hour. Previous investigations have indicated that 1991 and 1995 produced strong year classes. Preliminary results of the 1999 angler creel survey found angling pressure continuing to rise. Most anglers surveyed lived over 30 miles from Rainy Lake. Anglers kept about the same number of walleye per trip, however, with the highest angling pressure ever, an estimated 50,166 walleyes weighing 52,576 pounds were taken from Rainy Lake in 1999.

Trends in the long-term data show signs that the Rainy Lake walleye fishery continues to recover from years of overharvest and continual suppression seen through the early 1990s. The walleye gill net CPUE (catch per unit effort: number per net) was 6.95. For the past 10 years walleye CPUE has been at historically high levels. Gill net CPUE was at the seventh highest level since the large lake program began in 1983. Rainy Lake walleye abundance has reached a new peak. Walleye CPUE from 1983 to 1994 averaged 3.98 per net, since 1995 the average is 6.92 per net. Only twice (2001 and 2002) during the past nine years has the walleye CPUE been below six per net. Consistent recruitment has been the main factor contributing to the observed increase in CPUE. The walleye catch consisted of 12 age groups. Ages ranged from age-1 to age-17 with a mean of 4.59 years. Age-3 walleye made up 44.9% of the gill-net catch while age-7 accounted for 11.6%. Of the cohorts represented, the 1991, 1994, 1995, 1997, and 2001 cohorts are considered strong year-classes.Recruitment, expressed as year-class strength, is more consistent and higher than it was 15 years ago. Prior to the 1990s Rainy Lake walleye produced a strong year-class once every four years. Throughout the 1990s, six out of the 10 year-classes were rated as strong. Netting surveys show that the 2000 year-class is weak. However, the 2001 year-class stands to be the strongest on record. Early indications of the 2002 and 2004 year-classes are weak. The 2003 year-class is showing moderate abundances early on. Lengths of gill netted walleye ranged from 6.9 to 23.9 inches. The mean walleye length was 13.2 inches and the mean weight was 1.06 pounds. The CPUE of walleye over 17 inches in length was 1.65, which was above the third quartile for Rainy Lake. Catch rates of larger walleye (over 17") has significantly increased in the past 30 years. During the past 10 years the CPUE of walleye over 17 inches has remained greater than one per net, a feat that was achieved only twice prior to 1990. Currently walleye greater than 17 inches (and less than 28 inches) are protected by length regulations. The northern pike gill-net CPUE was 2.30, which is the long-term mean for Rainy Lake. Northern pike lengths ranged from 18.9 to 32.9 inches. The mean length was 23.1 inches. The mean weight was 2.71 pounds.Spring trap net sampling indicated the black crappie population is in great condition. The catch rate of crappies was at a record high during 2004. Currently, three very strong black crappie year-classes are in the desired length range (>10") and will provide good angling opportunities for the next few years. The 1998 year-class ranks as the strongest on record. This year-class was caught at a higher rate than any other year-class regardless of age. Besides the impressive 1998 year-class, the 1997 and 1995 year-classes were captured in record numbers. Smallmouth bass numbers from the nighttime electrofishing indicates good recruitment. The 2004 smallmouth bass CPUE was below normal for Rainy Lake. Smallmouth bass populations have grown and have been protected only by the catch-and-release ethics common to most bass anglers. Results of the 2004 angler creel survey show that angling pressure was below the recent five-year average. The summer of 2004 was the coldest summer on record in northern Minnesota. The cold temperatures and high winds made fishing difficult at times. However, the 2004 estimate of 236,944 angling hours was the sixth highest on record. The five-year mean on Rainy Lake is approximately 251,000 angler hours.Walleye were the most common fish species anglers sought, caught and harvested. Of the 88,107 walleye caught by anglers, 26,780 were harvested for a total yield of 25,783 pounds or 0.48 pounds per acre. An estimated 61,327 (140,904 pounds) walleye were caught and released by anglers during the 2004 open-water season. Of those walleye released an estimated 4,470 (8,734 pounds) died as a result of hooking mortality. Anglers targeting walleye reported catch and harvest rates of 0.435 and 0.135 fish per angler hour, respectively.

The 2007 large lake sampling program provided valuable insight to the status of the Rainy Lake fishery. Walleye, yellow perch, northern pike, smallmouth bass, and black crappie populations are doing well as indicated by various sampling methods. Several trends in the long-term gill net data show the Rainy Lake walleye fishery has recovered from years of overharvest and continual suppression seen through the early 1990s.

For the past 13 years walleye gill net CPUE has been at historically high levels. The 2007 CPUE was slightly down from the past 3 years, but still above the long-term mean. Walleye CPUE from 1983 to 1994 averaged 3.98 per net, since 1995 the average is 7.07 per net. Only twice (2001 and 2002) during the past ten years has the walleye CPUE been below six per net. Consistent recruitment has been the main factor contributing to the observed increase in CPUE.

The slight decline in walleye abundance in the gill nets can largely be attributed to poor production during 2002 and 2004. Age-5 and age-3 walleye typically make up a large portion of the gill net catch. In 2007, both age-5 and age-3 walleye were caught at very low rates for their respective ages. Their absence and the slight decline in CPUE is no reason for alarm as it reflects natural variation in walleye production.

Catch rates of larger walleye (over 17") have significantly increased in the past 30 years. During the past 13 years the CPUE of walleye over 17 inches has remained greater than one per net, a feat that was achieved only twice prior to 1990. Currently walleye greater than 17 inches (and less than 28 inches) are protected by length regulations.

Recruitment, expressed as year-class strength, is more consistent and higher than it was 15 years ago. Prior to the 1990s Rainy Lake walleye produced a strong year-class once every four years. Throughout the 1990s, six out of the 10 year-classes were rated as strong. Netting surveys show that the 2000 year-class is weak. However, the 2001 year-class stands to be the strongest on record. Indications of the 2002 and 2004 year-classes are week. In contrast, the 2003 and 2006 are very strong.

Walleye fishing should remain exceptional on Rainy Lake. There are several strong year-classes within the protected slot that should provide good catch rates of large walleye and uphold reproduction. The 2003 year-class will continue to be the main contributor to the harvest. While the 2006 and 2007 year-classes are showing good potential, it will be a couple of years before they begin recruitment to the sport fishery.

Northern pike gill-net CPUE showed a sharp increase in 2007. Northern pike assessment shows there are several average year-classes present in the catch. The 2004 year-class has emerged as being strong. While large northern pike were present there was a downward trend in pike growth rates during the late 1990s into the early 2000s, this trend has changed and growth rates are increasing while recruitment is slowing. During the early 1990s mean northern pike length at age-3 was approximately 23 inches, during the late 1990s into the early 2000s length at age-3 dropped into the mid to upper teen range. In 2006 the mean northern pike length for age-3 was 21.9 inches, illustrating the faster growth rates.

Sauger abundance has steadily declined for the past 15 years. The CPUE observed in 2007 was the lowest ever. This trend may demonstrate density dependent and interspecies competition that influences the abundance and growth of walleye and sauger. Sauger fishing on Rainy Lake is a result of indirect catch, no angling parties contacted during 2007 were targeting sauger. Low sauger abundance and a healthy walleye fishery likely are the cause for effort being directed towards walleye.

Lake whitefish are commercially fished on Rainy Lake and there is very little sport-fishing effort directed toward this species. Annual commercial harvest of lake whitefish has remained below the target quota every year since 1999. FCIN provides a standardized methodology for the monitoring of this population. Based on three years of observation the lake whitefish population is showing no signs of overexploitation, however, more years of observation are needed to quantify this statement. Good recruitment in the past five years indicates the population is sustainable. FCIN is scheduled to be conducted again during the summer of 2008 and again in 2011-12.

Spring sampling indicated the black crappie population is doing very well. Younger year-classes were present and mortality (natural and fishing) has greatly reduced the population of the strong year-classes from the mid-1990s. The recruitment of the 2003 year-class to the sport fishery (and trap nets) has resulted in a very abundant fishery with exceptional opportunities to catch crappies. The current status of the fishery indicates that crappie fishing should be exceptional during the next few years as the 2003 year-class continues to grow to desirable lengths.

Smallmouth bass numbers from the nighttime electrofishing indicates good recruitment. The 2007 smallmouth bass CPUE was near normal for Rainy Lake. Smallmouth bass populations have grown and have been protected only by the catch-and-release ethics common to most bass anglers. Bass growth on Rainy Lake is slow compared to area and state averages. However, there are plenty of memorable and trophy sized smallmouth bass present as demonstrated by the catch during the spring electrofishing and reports from anglers. Angler opportunities in 2008 should remain good.

Yellow perch gill-net numbers were above average for Rainy Lake. The length distribution of perch captured in the gill nets was predominantly in the less than nine-inch category. However, larger individuals are common and should provide some decent harvest opportunities for the next few years. Recruitment has been exceptional for the past five years, providing a strong forage base.

Walleye

Eleven fish species were captured during the annual fall gill netting on Rainy Lake in 2011. Walleye made up 25.7% of the catch by number. Walleye and northern pike represented 61.5% of the catch by total weight.

The 2011 walleye gill net catch rate was 7.67 fish per net. The 1998 to 2010 mean catch rate (historical average) was 7.71. The 2011 gill-net catch rate was above the median of 5.47 for Rainy Lake. Catch rates of larger walleye (over 17") have increased in the past 30 years. The catch rate of walleye over 17 inches peaked in 2005 at 3.0 walleye per net before beginning a declining trend. After the catch rate of walleye over 17 inches in 2008 dipped below one per net for the first time since the protected slot was put in place it rebounded strongly to 1.88 per net in 2010. The catch rate of walleye over 17 inches in length was 1.63 in 2011, slightly lower than 2010 but above the normal range for Rainy Lake. Currently walleye greater than 17 inches (and less than 28 inches) are protected by length regulations. Creel data from 2011 indicated that walleye 17 inches or greater in length made up 29 percent of the total catch for 2011.
Lengths of gill netted walleye ranged from 4.2 to 27.3 inches. The average walleye length was 14.1 inches and the average weight was 1.21 pounds.

The walleye catch consisted of 18 age groups. Ages ranged from age-0 to age-20 with an average of 5.1 years. Age-5 walleye made up 26.6 percent of the gill-net catch and age-3 and age-4 made up 13.6 percent and 17.9 percent, respectively. Altogether, 11.1 percent of the catch was represented by individuals ten years of age or older. Of the cohorts represented in the gill net catch from the past 10 years, the 2001, 2003, 2006 and 2007 year-classes are considered strong.

For the past 17 years, walleye gill net catch rates have been at historically high levels. The walleye catch rate from 1983 to 1994 averaged 3.98 per net; since 1995 the average is 7.66 per net. The 2011 catch rate of 7.67 per gill net was up slightly from the 6.13 per gill net captured in 2010 and represents the third year of increase since 2008. Consistent recruitment has been the main factor contributing to the observed increase in walleye catch rates.

Recruitment, expressed as year-class strength, is more consistent and higher than it was 15 years ago. Prior to the 1990s, Rainy Lake walleye produced a strong year-class once every four years. Throughout the 1990s, six out of the ten year-classes were rated as strong. During the first half of the 2000s three of the seven year-classes recruited to date are strong including record breaking 2001 year class, and the 2006 year-class which recruited to the gear in 2009. The 2007 year class also appears strong, marking the first time since 1997-98 that Rainy Lake has produced consecutive strong year classes.

Since 1996 walleye growth rates on Rainy Lake have decreased. Length at capture for walleye in 2011 was less than the historical average. This decrease in growth coincided with an increase in walleye abundance. These observations indicate potential density-dependent growth. Hartman and Margraf (1992) found that high densities of walleye (strong year-classes) suppressed the forage base and consequently reduced walleye growth in Lake Erie. On Rainy Lake this relation has not been demonstrated; specifically, there has been no discernable decreasing trend in the forage (yellow perch) abundance but rather an increase in yellow perch abundance since 2003 based on fall gill netting. The observed growth pattern may be the fisheries return to pre-overexploited growth rates.

Walleye fishing should remain exceptional on Rainy Lake. There are several strong year-classes within the protected slot that should provide good catch rates of large walleye and uphold reproduction. The 2006 and 2007 year-classes will continue to be the main contributors to the harvest.

Northern Pike

The northern pike gill-net catch rate was 1.93, which is at the normal range for Rainy Lake, but above the median for Lake Class 2 lakes statewide. Northern pike lengths ranged from 14.3 to 37.0 inches. The mean length was 22.4 inches and the mean weight was 2.79 pounds.

Age-3 and age-4 northern pike made up 26.7 percent of the northern pike catch, while age-2 made up 24.4 percent of the northern pike catch. Northern pike ages ranged from age-1 to age-13. The mean northern pike age was 3.9 years. The calculation of the year-class strength index indicated that there has not been a strong year-class of northern pike since 2005. However, early indications suggest that 2009 may be strong.

The northern pike gillnet catch rate decreased to below the normal range for Rainy Lake in 2009 after a sharp increase in 2007 and equally sharp decline in 2008. The 2010 northern pike catch rate rebounded slightly, but remained below the normal range for Rainy Lake. The 2011 catch continued the upward trend landing near the bottom end of the normal range for Rainy Lake. Northern pike assessment shows there were only two individuals from strong year-classes present in the catch (1998 and 2000 year-classes).

Sauger

The sauger catch rate of 2.67 fish per gill net continued the upward trend which began in 2010. The 2011 sauger catch rate was above the normal range for the Rainy Lake historical record but below the historical median. Sauger lengths ranged from 7.2 to 16.1 inches. The mean length was 10.4 inches with a mean weight of 0.33 pounds.

Age-3 and age-4 sauger each represented 21.9 percent of the sauger catch in the 2011 gill net catch while age-1 sauger made up an additional 18.8 percent of the catch. The mean sauger age was 3.6 years. The year-class strength index indicates that 2001 was the most recent strong year-class of sauger produced in Rainy Lake.

Sauger abundance has steadily declined for the past 16 years. The catch rate observed in 2011 was an increase from the record low values recorded in 2008 and 2009. This declining trend may demonstrate density dependent and interspecies competition that influences the abundance and growth of walleye and sauger. Staggs and Ottis (1996) found that competition did exist between walleye and sauger and that regardless both species grew better in years with high forage abundance.

Yellow Perch

The yellow perch catch rate of 9.58 fish per gill net was above the normal range for Rainy Lake and above the third quartile for all Lake Class 2 lakes. Yellow perch ranged in length from 5.0 to 12.6 inches, with a mean of 8.1 inches and a mean weight of 0.31 pounds.

Age-4 yellow perch made up 29.1 percent of the perch catch and age-3 perch made up an additional 24.6 percent of the catch. Yellow perch from nine year-classes up to age-10 were represented in the 2011 gill-net catch. The 2005, 2006, and 2007 year-classes were all strong as were the 2001, 2002, and 2003 year-classes. The 2008 year class appears average. These consecutive strong year-classes are driving the recent increases in yellow perch gill net catch rates.

Yellow perch gill-net numbers appear to have increased in Rainy Lake since the consecutive low catch years of 2001 and 2002. The length distribution of perch captured in the gill nets was predominantly in the less than nine-inch category with just 15 percent of the catch larger than nine inches. However, the total number of yellow perch caught in gill nets in 2011 was higher than 2010, resulting in a greater number of nine inch or larger fish which should provide some good harvest opportunities for the next few years. With the exception of 2004, recruitment has been exceptional for the past ten years with six of the seven best year-classes for Rainy Lake occurring since 2001. This strong yellow perch production should continue providing a good forage base and developing angling opportunities for years to come.

Smallmouth Bass

Due to short staffing, spring electrofishing targeting smallmouth bass took place during a single sampling event on the night of June 14th through June 15th resulting in fewer stations being sampled than previous years. A total of 6,375 seconds (1.77 hours) of "on-time" were recorded. The total smallmouth bass catch was 24 for a catch rate of 13.6 fish per hour. This catch rate is slightly lower than recent years but within the range observed in past surveys. Smallmouth bass ranged in length from 10.7 to 19.25 inches in length with a mean of 13.8 inches. Age-5 smallmouth bass represented 39.1 percent of the bass catch with age-7 contributing 21.7 percent. Based on spring electrofishing catch rates, the 2001, 2002, 2003, and 2006 year-classes are strong year classes.

Smallmouth bass growth on Rainy Lake is slow compared to area and state averages. However, there are plenty of memorable and trophy sized smallmouth bass present as demonstrated by the catch during the spring electrofishing and reports from anglers. Angler opportunities in 2012 should remain good.

Black Crappie

Annual trap netting targeting black crappie has been carried out in Black Bay since 1992 using standard lake survey trap nets. Trap netting consists of 20 set locations throughout Black Bay and the lower Rat Root River and was conducted from May 16 through May 18 in 2011. Length, weight, sex, maturity, and a scale sample were collected from captured black crappie.

A total of 35 black crappies were caught for a catch rate of 1.75 fish per net. This catch rate was slightly lower than the 2010 catch of 2.2 crappies per net and below the long-term average of 3.70 per net. Crappie lengths ranged from 7.95 to 13.66 inches with a mean of 11.61 inches. The 2003 and 2006 year-classes appear strong based on trap netting and the 2005 year-class is about average.

Although catch numbers were down slightly in 2011, spring sampling indicated the black crappie population is doing well. The recruitment of the 2003 year-class to the sport fishery (and trap nets) in 2009 has resulted in an abundant fishery with exceptional opportunities to catch crappies. The 2008 creel reported the highest harvest of crappies ever recorded for Rainy Lake. The variable recruitment of crappie in Rainy Lake is consistent with crappie populations from around the country (Sammons et al 2002 and Allen 1997). The current status of the fishery indicates that crappie fishing should be good during the next couple years as the strong 2003 year-class continues to contribute larger fish and the 2006 year class continues to provide numbers for harvest. An early and relatively warm spring in 2010 and good numbers of black crappie sampled in seines suggest that a strong year-class of black crappie may have been produced on Rainy Lake in 2010.

Other species

No lake whitefish were captured in standard gill nets in Rainy Lake in 2011. Black bullhead, black crappie, brown bullhead, longnose sucker, smallmouth bass, and rock bass were also captured in the 2011 gill nets.

Relative sauger abundance has steadily declined from the catch rates observed in the mid-1990s and has been relatively stable near the first quartile for Rainy Lake. Yellow perch gill net numbers appear to have increased in Rainy Lake since the consecutive low catch years of 2001 and 2002. The length distribution of perch captured in the gill nets suggest larger fish are more common in Rainy Lake than in the past as 24 percent of the perch caught in gill nets in 2012 were nine inches or longer. This increase in larger fish should provide some good harvest opportunities for the next few years. With the exception of 2004, recruitment has been exceptional for the past 11 years with six of the seven best year-classes for Rainy Lake occurring since 2001. This strong yellow perch production should continue providing a strong forage base and angling opportunities.
